      <comment>Added rules of inference navbox</comment>
      <text xml:space="preserve">{{Rules of inference}}
{{Unreferenced|date=May 2009}}
'''Conjunction introduction''' is the [[inference]] that, if ''p'' is true, and ''q'' is true, then the [[logical conjunction|conjunction]] ''p and q'' is true.

For example, if it's true that it's raining, and it's true that I'm inside, then it's true that it's raining, and I'm inside.

Formally:

:&lt;math&gt;p\,\!&lt;/math&gt;
:&lt;math&gt;\frac{q\,\!\qquad\quad}{}&lt;/math&gt;
:&lt;math&gt;( p \wedge q )&lt;/math&gt;

[[Category:Rules of inference]]
[[Category:Logic]]


{{logic-stub}}

[[pt:Introdução da conjunção]]
[[sv:Och-introducering]]</text>
