      <text xml:space="preserve">{{Redirect|Chinese food|the Americanized version|American Chinese cuisine}}
{{pp-semi|small=yes}}{{Cuisine of China}}
'''Chinese cuisine''' is any of several styles originating in the regions of [[China]], some of which have become highly popular in other parts of the world&amp;nbsp;– from [[Asia]] to the [[Americas]], [[Australia]], [[Western Europe]] and [[Southern Africa]].

==Staples==
===Rice===
In general, rice is the major food source for people from rice farming areas in southern China. It is most commonly eaten in the form of [[steamed rice]]. Rice is also used to produce [[beers]], [[baijiu|wine]]s and vinegars. In wheat farming areas in Northern China, people largely rely on flour based food such as [[noodles]], [[breads]], [[jiaozi|dumpling]]s and [[mantou|steamed buns]].&lt;ref name=Yao&gt;Yao, Zhang. ''China Everyday!''. Page One Pub. 2007. ISBN 9279812453303&lt;/ref&gt;

===Noodles===
Noodles come dry or fresh in a variety of sizes, shapes and textures and are often served in soups and fried as toppings and some varieties such as [[Shou Mien]] (壽麵, literally noodles of longevity) are symbolic of long life and good health according to Chinese tradition.&lt;ref name=Yao /&gt; [[Tofu]], made of [[soy beans]] is another popular product to supply protein.&lt;ref name=Hsieh&gt;J. Li &amp; Y. Hsieh. ''Traditional Chinese Food Technology and Cuisine''. Asia Pacific Journal of Clinical Nutrition. 2004;13(2): 147–155.&lt;/ref&gt;

===Wheat===
{{Empty section|date=April 2011}}

===Vegetables===
{{Empty section|date=April 2011}}

===Herbs===
{{Empty section|date=April 2011}}

===Seasonings===
When comes to sauces, China is home to soy sauce which is made from fermented soya beans and wheat. Oyster sauce, transparent rice vinegar, Chinkiang black rice vinegar, fish sauce, [[furu|fermented tofu]](furu) are also widely used.

Spices and seasonings such as fresh root [[ginger]], [[garlic]], [[spring onion]], [[white pepper]], [[sesame oil]] are widely used in many regional cuisines. [[Sichuan peppercorn]]s, [[star anise]], [[cinnamon]], [[fennel]], [[clove]]s.&lt;ref name=times&gt;[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/food_and_drink/real_food/article4262148.ece Times Online Ching He Huang 10 basic ingredients for Chinese cooking]&lt;/ref&gt;

To give extra flavors to dishes, many Chinese cuisines also contain dried Chinese mushrooms, dried baby shrimps, dried tangerine peel,&lt;ref name=nytimes&gt;[http://www.nytimes.com/1993/06/02/garden/chinese-restaurants-are-adding-herbs-for-flavor-and-health.html Chinese Restaurants Are Adding Herbs for Flavor and Health] – ''[[The New York Times]]&lt;/ref&gt; dried Sichuan chillies as well.

===Desserts===
==Regional cuisines==
{{Expand section|date=April 2011}}
[[File:Billyfood16.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Beef noodle soup]]]]
[[File:BCfood10.JPG|thumb|upright|[[Chinese fried rice]]]]
a number of different styles contribute to Chinese cuisine, but perhaps the best known and most influential are [[Szechuan cuisine|Sichuan cuisine]], [[Shandong cuisine]], [[Jiangsu cuisine]] and [[Guangdong cuisine|Guangdong (Cantonese) cuisine]].&lt;ref name=&quot;Yao&quot;/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.kas.ku.edu/archived-site/chinese_food/regional_cuisine.html Regional chinese cuisines, edu site]&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.travelchinaguide.com/intro/cuisine_drink/cuisine/eight_cuisines.htm Chinese Eight Cuisines]&lt;/ref&gt; These styles are distinctive from one another due to factors such as available resources, climate, [[Geography of China|geography]], [[History of China|history]], cooking techniques and lifestyle. One style may favour the use of lots of garlic and [[shallots]] over lots of chilli and spices, while another may favour preparing [[seafood]] over other meats and [[fowl]]. Jiangsu cuisine favours cooking techniques such as [[braising]] and stewing, while Sichuan cuisine employs baking, scalding, and wrapping, just to name a few.&lt;ref name=Yao /&gt; Hairy [[crab]] is a highly sought after local delicacy in [[Shanghai]], as it can be found in lakes within the region. [[Beijing]] [[Peking Duck|Roast Duck]] (otherwise known as 'Peking Duck') is another popular dish which is well known outside China.&lt;ref name=Yao /&gt; Based on the raw materials and ingredients used, the method of preparation, and cultural differences, a variety of foods with different flavours and textures are prepared in different regions of the country. Many traditional regional cuisines rely on basic methods of preservation such as drying, salting, [[pickling]] and [[fermentation]].&lt;ref name=Hsieh&gt;J. Li &amp; Y. Hsieh. ''Traditional Chinese Food Technology and Cuisine''. Asia Pacific Journal of Clinical Nutrition.&lt;/ref&gt;

===Lu (Shangdong)===
===Yue (Hong Kong and Guangdong)===
{{Expand section|date=April 2011}}
[[Dim Sum]], literally &quot;touch your heart&quot;,  is a [[Cantonese]] term for small hearty dishes.&lt;ref name=Yao /&gt; These bite-sized portions are prepared using traditional cooking methods such as frying, steaming, stewing and baking. It is designed so that one person may taste a variety of different dishes. Some of these may include [[Rice noodle roll|rice rolls]], [[Lo mai gai|lotus leaf rice]], [[turnip cake]]s, buns, shui [[jiaozi|jiao]]-style dumplings, [[stir-fry|stir-fried]] green vegetables, [[congee]] [[porridge]], soups, etc. The Cantonese style of dining, [[yum cha]], combines the variety of dim sum dishes with the drinking of [[tea]]. Yum cha literally means 'drink tea'.&lt;ref name=Yao /&gt;

